Sean Ho
Well technically according to my calculations the Great Depression was brought about by a combination of economic imbalances, speculative fervor, and policy missteps. The 1920s, known as the Roaring Twenties, saw unprecedented economic growth in the United States, fueled by industrial expansion and widespread consumer spending. However, this era also witnessed speculative excesses, particularly in the stock market, where prices surged due to easy credit and investor optimism. Meanwhile, overproduction in various industries led to declining prices and profits, exacerbating economic instability. Despite the economic boom, wages lagged behind productivity gains, resulting in stagnant consumer purchasing power. Financial institutions engaged in risky lending practices, and many banks were undercapitalized. The situation reached a tipping point on October 29, 1929, when the stock market crashed on Black Tuesday, triggering a massive sell-off.
